@node Introduction "Announce v2.0 Documentation"

Introduction
~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you are running a multi-node board, you just HAVE to try this tool!
It's a really pleasant thing to have installed, for you and your users.

What is does? Well, when a user logs on, it notifies the users who are
already online (on the other nodes) of the logon. You can also make it
notify them of logoffs (and loss carriers). If a message can't be sent
because the user is doing something (uploading, reading bulletins etc),
the message is queued. When he becomes idle again, he instantly gets all
his waiting logon/logoff messages. Here is an example of how that can
look:

>>> Announce v2.0 by Aquarius/OTL <<<
     ( Current time: 17:14:00 )

HardHack logged in on node 3 at 17:07:37.
Erod logged off from node 1 at 17:09:13.

>>>>
@endnode

@node Requirements "Announce v2.0 Documentation"

Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~
An Amiga with OS 2.0 or higher.
AmiExpress/SigmaExpress.
(The door works for sure on /X v2.20-3.38 and possibly on other versions
too.)

@endnode

@node Installation "Announce v2.0 Documentation"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~
First create the directory 'Doors:Announce', and copy the correct version
of the door there. AnnLogon.10 is for AmiExpress versions below 3.30 and
for SigmaExpress. AnnLogon.32 is for AmiExpress 3.30 or higher.

/X 2.xx, SigmaExpress:

Add the following line to your SYS.Cmd file:

-----Cut-here-------------------------------
*ANNLOGON XM005Doors:Announce/AnnLogon.10
-------Cut-here-----------------------------

/X 3.xx:

Copy 'annlogon.info' to your SYSCmd directory and check that its tooltype
LOCATION is correct.


Run the door with MCI in the Logon.txt. Don't worry, the door is totally
invisible to the on-logging users. Every Logon.txt should start with the
following:

-----Cut-here-------------
~
~CC_ANNLOGON|
-------Cut-here-----------


The logoff notifier is not necessary to install (in contrast to the logon
notifier) but I really recommend that you do it (it's nice!). Then copy
AnnLogoff to Doors:Announce/. Run it in the logoff scripts, preferably
among the first commands. You must supply two arguments: the node number
and the node location (defined in ACP.info for /X 3.xx) which for most
sysops is the same as the bbs location (bbs:). For example, in the logoff
script for node 2, write this line:

-----Cut-here------------------------
Doors:Announce/AnnLogoff 2 BBS:
-------Cut-here----------------------

(Provided that the location for the directory 'Node2' is 'BBS:'.)

Perhaps you shouldn't put it in the script for your local node, since you
probably always logon with F1 and therefore by-pass Logon.txt and the
logon notifier. It would probably confuse your users if they only got the
message that you logged off, and they hadn't even noticed that you were
online.
@endnode

@node MiscInfo "Announce v2.0 Documentation"

Miscellaneous Info
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The first time the door (AnnLogon.xx) is used, it stays in memory as a
'host task' that will perform all the actual message sending to the nodes
at the right times. Therefore, no logoff messages can be sent before the
logon notifier has been used. But the logon notifier is normally started
first so this shouldn't be any problem. If the logoff notifier is run
first, nothing happens (no system crash if that's what you thought).

If you want to change to another version of the door (from 10-node to
32-node for example) or you want to reset Announce (clear all waiting
messages), you will first need to remove the door from memory.

That is accomplished by sending it a CTRL-C signal, for example by using
the AmigaDOS 'break' command. If you don't know how to do that I can tell
you... Open a shell and type 'status', which shows all loaded processes.
One of them should be Doors:Announce/AnnLogon or something. Notice the
process number for it. Then type 'break <process>', for example 'break 8'
if the process number was 8. Type 'status' again and the process should be
gone.
@endnode

